{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060205A/1937111401/0667.xml":{"full_text":"BlIUtLEY TO SEEK\nLESS PROFITS IA)\nPlans Amendments Durinj\nSession to Ease Load on\nSmall Firms.\nMr the Associated Press.\nCLEVELAND, Nov. 13.\u2014Senato\nRobert J. Bulkley, Democrat, of Ohi\nannounced today he planned to intro\nduce in the special session of Con\ngress amendments to the undistributet\nprofits tax \u201cto ease the burden oi\nsmaller corpora\ntions and ellmi\nVv iV.OWiV.ViVU\non business ex\npansion.\u201d\nThe announce\nment by Senato\nBulkley, membe\nof the Senat\nFinance Commit\ntee, came as con\ngressional leader\nindicated ther\nwas little likeli\nhood of action o\nmsmmMmmm tax revision dui\nSenator Bulkier. ln* the sPeci\u00a3\nsession startln\nMonday. Senator Bulkley has votei\nwith the administration on most o\nIts measures.\nSenator Bulkley's amendments woult\nprovide:\n1. Flat exemption for all corpora\ntions up to $50,000 net profit.\n2. For all corporations, deduction\nequal to net losses for two years las\npreceding.\n3. Allowance as a deduction in com\nputing the undistributed profits tai\nto the extent of one-half the cos'\nof any amounts actually expende\nfor replacements or new' constructior\nnew machinery and equipment, or ne\\\nimprovements during the taxable yeai\nSenator Bulkley said \"I votei\n\u2022gainst the enactment of the presen\nUndistributed prots tax law, believ\ning it would have an unnecessaril;\nrestrictive effect on business.\n\"However, there is enough merit ii\nthe general principle underlying th'\nlaw to justify its retention provide!\nthe mor^ burdensome features of i\ncan be cured by amendments, and i\nis to this end that I am directing th\npresent proposal.\u201d\n\nCongress\n(Continued From First Page.)\nIs confirmed by Majority Leade\nBarkley.\nAnti-Lynching Bill.\nWhen Congres adjourned, the Sen\nate had entered an agreement an'\nspecial order that the anti-lynchin\nbill should be considered immediate!\nafter the farm bill had been dispose'\nof, in the next session. This orde\n\u2022till stands. When it was made, th\nexpectation was that the farm bil\nwould be the first taken up in th\nSenate. Since no farm bill is read\n\u2014and it may be weeks before it i\nready\u2014Senator Barkley and other\nare intent upon going ahead wit!\nthe other measures on the progran\nuntil the Agricultural Committee i\nready to report. Whether the sup\nporters of the anti-lynching bill, whicl\nhas been reported to the Senate, wil\nacquiesce gracefully or make a figh\nto have their bill considered withou\nfurther delay remains to be seen.\nIntent upon a balanced budget ir\nthe fiscal year 1939, the President wil\neye the new farm bill carefully, par\nticularly if it calls for additional gov\nernmental expenditures as it is ex\npected to do. He has said to thi\nchairman of the agricultural commit\ntees that if legislation is enacte<\ncausing increased expenditures, nev\nrevenues must also be provided. Thi;\nhas caused a revival of talk of thi\nold processing taxes to meet farn\nbenefit payments. Increased bene\nfits will have to be taken care o\neither through such taxes or througl\ndirect appropriation of public funds\nAnother stumbling block in the wa;\nof prompt consideration of farm leg\nislation is found in a difference o\nopinion whether crop control shall bi\ncompulsory or voluntary\u2014as in thi\npast. There is much distaste amoni\n4 some of the members for compulsor;\ncrop control. Senator Capper o\nKansas, for example, declared his op\nposition yesterday. But whether thi\ncrop control is compulsory or volun\ntary, the plan is to make benefit pay\nments for curtailment of crops, elthei\ndirectly or through the so-called soi\nconservation program, now in effect\nFavors Referendum.\nSenator Capper declared himself ir\nfavor of a provision carried in the\nPope-McGill farm bill of last session\nregarded as more or less the adminis\ntration bill, which would submit tc\nthe farmers any crop-control plan foi\na referendum vote. A two-thirds vote\nof the farmers would be required tc\nadopt the plan.\nWhen Chairman Mary Norton ol\nthe House Labor Committee has had\nan opportunity to confer with the\nHouse leaders, the procedure foi\nbringing the wages and hours bill be\nfore the House will be determined\nMrs. Norton has in mind certair\namendments to the pending bill\namong them placing the administra\ntion of the law in the Department ol\nLabor instead of the proposed boarc\nof five members. In the Senate there\nis sentiment in favor of considering\nanew, and as a new bill, the wage:\nand hours measure if it is vitallj\namended by the House, rather thar\nmerely leaving the bill to a confer\nence committee of the two houses te\nwhip into shape.\nMembers of Congress have beer\n\u2022low in returning to Washington foi\nthe opening of the special session\nThose who are here, however, arc\nparticularly insistent that something\nbe done without delay to encourage\nbusiness and to relieve business, as fai\nas possible, of burdensome taxation\nBtuator Pat Harrison of Mississippi\nnot waiting to reach Washington, has\ntelegraphed Secretary of the Treasury\nt Morgenthau that he believes some\nthing should be done without delay\nto revise the undistributed profits tax.\nHe added that he intended to take\nthe matter up as soon as he reaches\nWashington.\nTax legislation, under the Constitu\ntion, must originate in the House. For\n10 days a subcommittee of the House\nr Ways and Means Committee has been\nat work on the matter of tax revision,\nwith daily reports placed before it\nby the Treasury officials. Representa\n1 tive Treadway of Massachusetts, rank\ning Republican member of the com\nr mittee, said last night:\ni \u201cThe two principal subjects dis\nr cussed so far have been changes in\nthe undistributed profits tax and the\n1 capital gains tax. Undoubtedly the\nsubcommittee, in its final recommen\nf dations, will make material changes\ns in these levies.\u201d\n\"Penalty Not a Tax.\u201d\nSpeaking of the undistributed tax,\ni Mr. Treadway said that it is \u201creally a\npenalty and not a tax, working the\ni greatest hardship on those least able\nI to pay. It has discouraged business\nexpansion and re-employment, and\nundermined the stability of the whole\nbusiness structure. Unquestionably it\nhas been a large factor in the pres\nent Roosevelt slump.\u201d\nMr. Treadway said it was noticeable\nthat the man who had represented the\nadministration at the time of the\nenactment of the undistributed profits\ntax, Herman Oliphant, \"has been con\nI spicuous by his absence,\u201d and, he\ni added, \u201cthis is a good omen.\u201d\n1 The Massachusetts member de\ndared himself heartily in favor of the\ni recommendations of Secretary Mor\ngenthau, made last Wednesday, that\nthe budget be balanced and govern\n1 mental expenditures be cut. Morgen\nthau, he said, had announced a pro\ngram of interesting private enter\nprise in business expansion. Unless\nconfidence can be restored by a change\nof attitude on the part of the admin\nOration, jt will be difficult to put\nthis idea into effect, Treadway in\nsisted.\nSenator Chavez, Democrat, of New\nMexico on the eve of the special\nsession issued a statement in which\nhe. too, demanded that something be\ndone by the administration to modify\nthe \"excess profits tax.\u201d He said:\n\u201cThere appears to be a general un\ncertainty today concerning the exact\nposition of business. In my opinion,\nthe American people are demanding\nCongress to make a forthright ex\npression of its attitude toward busi\nness. I, for one, feel that business\nshould be given a chance and that\nCongress give this opportunity by an\nimmediate modification of the excess\nprofits tax.\n\"Further along these lines I con\ncur whole-heartedly with Senator Har\nrison's position on Secretary Morgen\nthau\u2019s views with respect to the neces\nsity for economy in Government. Un\nnecessary agencies should be abolished.\nReorganization is badly needed. Du\nplication in functions of Government\nare numerous and should be done\naway with. However, all necessary\nfunds required to care for the needy\nof the country will have to be ex\npended. This does not mean that\nneedless experimentation has to con\ntinue.\u201d\nOther Statement.\nIn a statement issued last night\nDiller, Republican, of Pennsylvania\nsaid:\n\"Congress assembles in a period of\neconomic hesitancy. The first objec\ntive of all parties should be to check\nthe business recession now in flow.\nFor the most part this can be accom\nplished quickly by the mere act of\ncorrecting some of the more disastrous\nblunders of New Deal policy during\nthe last four years. ^This session\nshould go down in history as the\nFirst Congress of Corrections.\n\u201cForemost among the urgent needs\nof the hour is drastic modification, if\nnot outright repeal, of the crazy-quilt\nscheme of taxation upon undistributed\nbusiness profits, enacted last year\nunder the White House political lash.\n\u201cSecondly, an honest effort must be\nmade to bring Federal finances into\norder. Nor can this be accomplished\nmerely by taking Social Security trust\nfunds and spending them for current\nextravagar cies. Neither will a \u2018lay\nman's balance\u2019 restore investment\nconfidence, if accomplished by devious\ntricks of Treasury bookkeeping.\u2019\u2019\nVice President Garner returned to\nWashington yesterday, in fine fettle\nfor the coming session. He was wel\ncomed at the Union Station by the\nSecretary of the Senate, Col. Edwin\nA. Halsey. At noon he went to the\nWhite House to confer with the Pres\nident.\nOutside of the reading of the Pres\nident\u2019s message at the opening session\ntomorrow, the proceedings in both the\nSenate and House are expected to be\nroutine. The Senator-elect from Ar\nkansas, John E. Miller, chosen to fill\nthe unexpired term of the late Demo\ncratic leader, Senator \u201cJoe\" Robinson,\nwill take the oath of office. Four\nnewly-elected members of the House,\nalso chosen to fill vacancies, including\nBruce Barton of New\u2019 York, are ex\npected to be sworn in also.\n\nWILCOX WILL SEEK\nPEPPER\u2019S SENATE SEAT\nHouse Member Announces He\nWill Be Candidate in Elec\ntion Next Year\nBy the Associated Press.\nWEST PALM BEACH, Fla., Nov.\n13-\u2014J. Mark Wilcox, Representative of\nthe fourth Florida district in Con\ngress, announced his candidacy today\nfor the United States Senate seat now\noccupied by Claude Pepper of Talla\nhassee.\nWilcox is serving his third term as\nRepresentative in his district, which\nembraces the southeast section of the\nState.\nSenator Pepper was elected last year\nto fill the vacancy created by the death\nof Senator Duncan U. Fletcher and\nmust stand for renomination and re\nelection next year.\nPool Yields Boys\u2019 Treasures\nf\ni\nEleven-Year-Old Oscar Walker, left, of 2132 H street N.W.\nand Harry Young, 15, of 2136y2 H street N.W. were on hand\ni yesterday to salvage whatever they felt was worth keeping as\nt workmen drained the Lincoln Reflecting Pool for one of its\nperiodic cleanings. Golf balls and a small fish were the boys\u2019\nprincipal prizes. Larger fish were caught by other boys during\nthe operation.\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nHarllee Branch Also Is In\njured in North Caro\nlina Accident.\nTwo members of Congress and Sec\nond Postmaster General Harllee\nBranch were Injured in automobile\naccidents In North Carolina yester\nday and last night.\nThe most seriously injured was\nRepresentative John M. Costello of\nCalifornia who suffered possible frac\ntures of the legs and internal injuries,\nthe Associated Press reported from\nFayetteville.\nIn another accident near Southern\nPines, Mr. Branch and Representa\ntive Lambeth of the eighth North\nCarolina district, were slightly in\njured in a collision while en route to\nthe Duke North Carolina football\ngame.\nMr. Costello and J. A. Cummings, a\nmarine of Wallace, N. C., said to have\nbeen driving the car, were taken to a\nhospital at Fayetteville last night\nafter, it was said, their car got out\nof control and overturned. Persons\nwho took the two to the hospital said\nRepresentative Costello's condition ap\npeared serious. Later, however, hos\npital attaches said Costello's condition\nwas not serious but that they could\nnot disclose his injuries pending an\nX-ray report.\nMr. Lambeth suffered a strained\nligament in his leg, but said the in\njury\u00abwould not interfere with his at\ntendance at the opening of the spe\ncial session of Congress tomorrow'.\nMr. Branch was only slightly hurt, it\nwas said. Both men, however, aban\ndoned plans for attending the game.\n\nA. F. OF L. OPPOSES\nPRESIDENT\u2019S PLAN\nLabor Features of Building Stim\nulation Scheme Draw Edi\ntorial Attack.\nBj the Associated Press.\nAmerican Federation of Labor praise\nfor \u201cprevailing wage\u201d requirements in\nFederal slum-clearance activities indi\ncated anew yesterday its opposition to\nlabor features of President Roosevelt\u2019s\nbuilding stimulation plan.\nWithout mentioning the President\u2019s\nplan, an editorial in the Federation\u2019s\nweekly news service described as \u201cmost\nimportant\u201d the labor provision of the\nWagner Housing Act. These require\npayment of prevailing wages, mainte\nnance of maximum hours of work and\nobservance of workmen's compensation\nlaws.\nEarlier last week. William Green,\nA. F. of L. president, expressed doubt\nthat Mr. Roosevelt's plan was \"prac\nticable and workable,\u201d although saying\nit was worthy of consideration.\nThe President had suggested that\nbuilding craftsmen might accept a\nlower hourly wage in return for a\nguaranteed minimum anual Income.\nBuilding trades workmen now receive\nhigh hourly wages, but often are with\nout employment for long periods.\nAfter praising the Wagner Act\u2019s\nlabor provisions, the editorial added:\n\u201cIn this connection, it is appropriate\nto point out that the Wagner Housing\nAct would not have successfully sur\nvived the stormy attacks made on it\nin the last Congress under the guise\nof economy if organized labor in all\nsections of the United States had not\nstrongly and persistently asserted its\ndemand for a permanent housing pro\ngram.\u201d\nU. S. ASKED TO PARLEY\nCub* Also Send* Bid to Mexico\nand Santo Domingo.\nHAVANA, Nov. 13 UP).\u2014The Cuban\nstate department will ask the govern\nments of the United States, Mexico\nand Santo Domingo to confer with\nrepresentatives of Cuba and Haiti on\nthe recent Haiti-Santo Domingo fric\ntion, it was learned tonight.\nPresident Stenio Vincent of Haiti\ncommunicated with President Federico\nLaredo Bru of Cuba asking him to seek\nto bring about a conference with the\nother countries. President Laredo Bru\naccepted the commission, it was\nlearned, and instructed the state de\npartment to proceed at once to make\nthe necessary representations.\nI\nInjured\nREPRESENTATIVE\nCOSTELLO.\nONCE F.A.C.B. CHIEF\nFormer Alcohol Administra\ntor Served 20 Years on\nChildren\u2019s Court.\nFranklin Chase Hoyt, former Federa\nalcohol administrator and justice o\nthe Children's Court in New York fo;\nnearly 20 years, died yesterday in Nev\nYork, according to the Associate!\nPress.\njuage Moyt gave\nill health as one\nof the reasons for\nhis resignation as\nchairman of the\nFederal Alcohol\nControl B o a rd\nlast January 1\nafter less than\nfour months of\nservice. He was\n61 years old.\nHis letter of\nr p R i tr n a firm t\nPresident Roose- HT If kflMi\nvelt hinted dis-\nsatisfaction with u 0>\nthe liquor control set-up, but said h\nwas leaving because of \"a number o\npersonal reasons, the chief of whicl\nis a persistent throat condition tha\nhas been bothering me for some time.\nA native of Pelham, N. Y., Judg\nHoyt was a grandson of Salmon F\nChase, former Chief Justice of th\nUnited States. He began his lega\ncareer in New York in 1898, becam\nassistant corporation counsel In 190\nand legal adviser to the Mayor ii\n1905. He served as a justice in th\nCourt of Special Sessions from 190\nto 1927. Instrumental in organizatioi\nof the Children\u2019s Court of New York\nhe was appointed its first presidim\njustice in 1915, resigning in 1933 afte\nhandling more than 75,000 cases.\nHe was president of the Big Brothe\nmovement from 1911 to 1915 and wa\nelected honorary president of the Ne\\\nYork Council of the Boy Scouts o\nAmerica in 1918.\nGIBSONASKSPROBE\nOF TRADE SLUMP\n9\nSenator Urges Congression\nal Investigation of Busi\nness Conditions.\nA congressional investigation of\nbusiness conditions and methods\nneeded to Improve them was pro\nposed yesterday by Senator Gibson,\nRepublican, of Vermont.\nGibson said Senators of both par\nties assured him they would support\na resolution to set up a special Senate\ncommittee \"to investigate the causes\nof the present business let-down.\u201d\n\u201cWe should take immediate action\nto find out the Cause of the present\nsituation, having in mind that the\nprosperity of the country depends on\nthe prosperity of the small manufac\nturer,\u201d he said.\nGibson said both agriculture and\nlabor \"suffered\u201d during business re\ncessions and that any method found\nto improve business would affect them.\nMeanwhile, the National Associa\n1 tion of Manufacturers urged Congress\nto \u201chalt the present business reces\nsion and restore \u00bbnfidence by imme\ndiately relaxing tax handicaps and\nshelving plans for furnishing restric\ntions upon industry.\u201d\nIn an open letter to Congress Wil\nliam B. Warner, association president,\nsaid the \u201cconnection between the pres\nent business recession and the effect\nof laws which hamper the free flow\nof capital through private enterprise\n1 become plainer every day.\u201d\nIn addition to the proposal that\nimmediate steps be taken to aid busi\nness- Mr- Warner urged that the\nl Treasury and Revenue Committees of\nthe Senate and House hear and study\nfacts of business experience to show\nthe operating effect of the present\nawkward, ambiguous and frequently\ndestructive tax structure.\u201d He pro\nposed, however, that immediate action\nF not be deferred pending the outcome\nof such inquiries.\nEmphasizing the necessity of con\nfidence to permit business to take up\nslack in production and employment,\nMr. Warner cited a survey Just com\npleted by manufacturers in all lines of\nIndustry throughout the country as\nrevealing the situation now faced by\nbusiness.\n\u201cWhile 59.5 per cent of those reply\ning to our inquiry expected the same\nor better business during the next\nsix months,\u201d he said, \u201c40.5 per cent\nexpected less business activity.\n_ A\u20143\nSpecial Sunday Dinner, $1.50\nShore Dinner__$1.25\n12 Noon to B P.M.\nESTABLISHED IS SB\nMayflower HoUl Block 1107'\"conn. Aro.\nkoiore the\nSnow Flies!\nLet Chamberlin protect\nyour home with Weather\nStrips, Calking and Rock\nWool Insulation.\nYou Can Purchase These\nl on\nCONVENIENT TERMS\n12 to 36 Months\nEttimat** Free\nCHAMBERLIN METAL\nWEATHER STRIP CO.\n932 NEW YORK AVE.\nCall National 3655\n\n1938\nPflCEMflKER\nCORO\nUnderwood and\nRoyal Portables complete w.tm\nCAMYING CASE\nand INSTKUOION\n1 A WEEK ,00,!\nCAPITOL Tm?o,,T\u201c\n822 13th St. NA. 4858\nBF-HEARING I\nyour PROBLEM? 1\ninvite you to have a SELEX-A- 1\nof the RADIOEAR today. 1\nand only Laboratory Made\u00bbto-Order\nand one-fourth ounces\u2014the world's jfj\nruly effective Hearing Aid Microphone, a\nat has changed the character of a a\nThi, NEW and BETTER\n\u2018.1NG SERVICE I\nSHINGTON COMPANY f\nlg. District 2054 1\n4\nI EUREKA\nS\nGRAND PRIZE\nMQDEL No. 9\n*8-\u201d\nRebuilt\n5 Like Neu)\n\ni Just os good as if you paid\nthe original price of $45.\nCome in and see it or\nphone for free home\ndemonstration.\nI NAtional 7773-7774\nThe One and Only\n(best brrHdsJ\ns V Cotnpantf\n1\n805 11th St. N.W.\nOPEN EVENINtS\nflPTPfilVAn SKKTittH\nIStS 22!SSBSiii 22 ktJemanj\nBeginners\